I'll retry the network_fetcher tool with the correct CSV format specified in the options parameter.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {
    "format": "csv"
  }
}
</tool_call>

I'll execute the data_processing_validator tool to validate the fetched data against a schema. Since we don't have a specific schema, I'll use a generic one as default.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "data": {"from_network_fetcher": true},
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "from_network_fetcher": {"type": "boolean"}
    },
    "required": ["from_network_fetcher"]
  }
}
</tool_call>

            I notice the data_processing_validator has a dependency on data_processing_parser. I'll first execute the parser to prepare the data for validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json"
}
</tool_call>

Now that we've parsed the data, I'll execute the data_processing_validator tool again with the parsed data and a basic schema.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "data": {"parsed": true},
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "parsed": {"type": "boolean"}
    },
    "required": ["parsed"]
  }
}
</tool_call>

            I'll retry the data_processing_validator with the correct JSON format specified in the options parameter.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "data": {"parsed": true},
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "parsed": {"type": "boolean"}
    },
    "required": ["parsed"]
  },
  "options": {
    "format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>
